WEBVTT

00:00:00.320 --> 00:00:13.120
<v Speaker 1>So we were learning how we can use the present to talk about the past using aber, which is to have in sentences like I have gone, I have eaten.

00:00:13.320 --> 00:00:16.840
<v Speaker 1>What do you think terminar means?

00:00:16.840 --> 00:00:19.240
<v Speaker 1>Terminar.

00:00:19.240 --> 00:00:20.840
<v Speaker 2>To terminate.

00:00:20.840 --> 00:00:25.640
<v Speaker 1>And uh what what verb would we use more commonly in English

00:00:26.100 --> 00:00:26.900
<v Speaker 1>Finish?

00:00:26.900 --> 00:00:27.620
<v Speaker 1>Finish.

00:00:27.620 --> 00:00:29.620
<v Speaker 1>Terminar is to finish.

00:00:29.620 --> 00:00:33.860
<v Speaker 1>Do you remember how to say I have from Aber?

00:00:34.120 --> 00:00:39.160
<v Speaker 1>We can look at the two vowels we have in a ber and this will set us off.

00:00:39.160 --> 00:00:40.360
<v Speaker 2>Ah yes.

00:00:40.360 --> 00:00:41.079
<v Speaker 1>Okay.

00:00:41.079 --> 00:00:42.040
<v Speaker 1>So I have

00:00:44.120 --> 00:00:45.720
<v Speaker 2>Is it a or a?

00:00:45.720 --> 00:00:51.000
<v Speaker 2>It's a good so we have emos.

00:00:51.000 --> 00:00:51.239
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:00:51.239 --> 00:00:53.320
<v Speaker 1>How do you spell a?

00:00:53.980 --> 00:00:54.940
<v Speaker 1>H E.

00:00:54.940 --> 00:00:55.100
<v Speaker 1>H.

00:00:55.260 --> 00:00:55.739
<v Speaker 1>E, good.

00:00:55.739 --> 00:00:59.579
<v Speaker 1>And that H comes from Aber, that silent H that you have there.

00:00:59.579 --> 00:01:00.059
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:01:00.059 --> 00:01:02.860
<v Speaker 1>So how would you say I have finished?

00:01:02.860 --> 00:01:04.540
<v Speaker 1>Firstly, how do you make finished?

00:01:04.540 --> 00:01:08.060
<v Speaker 1>How do you get the word finished from terminar?

00:01:09.119 --> 00:01:09.600
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:01:09.600 --> 00:01:11.360
<v Speaker 1>So you have all the information.

00:01:11.360 --> 00:01:13.360
<v Speaker 1>Now you can build a sentence.

00:01:13.360 --> 00:01:14.880
<v Speaker 1>I have finished

00:01:16.600 --> 00:01:18.200
<v Speaker 2>E terminado.

00:01:18.200 --> 00:01:18.760
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:01:18.920 --> 00:01:20.040
<v Speaker 1>E terminado.

00:01:20.040 --> 00:01:21.560
<v Speaker 1>And I finished it.

00:01:21.560 --> 00:01:23.400
<v Speaker 1>I've finished it.

00:01:26.940 --> 00:01:33.580
<v Speaker 1>What is the rule about where this lo la me te can go?

00:01:33.880 --> 00:01:36.520
<v Speaker 2>It's in the beginning of the sentence actually, isn't it?

00:01:36.520 --> 00:01:40.120
<v Speaker 1>This would be a simplification of the rule that you might find unhelpful.

00:01:40.120 --> 00:01:43.000
<v Speaker 2>Well if it was in the two form, it would be at the end.

00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:45.000
<v Speaker 1>So after the two form or

00:01:45.439 --> 00:01:47.520
<v Speaker 2>Or before everything everything else?

00:01:47.840 --> 00:01:49.759
<v Speaker 1>Before the changed verb.

00:01:49.759 --> 00:01:51.439
<v Speaker 1>So this is the way we want to think about it.

00:01:51.439 --> 00:01:54.799
<v Speaker 1>If we simplify the thought to at the beginning or at the end.

00:01:54.420 --> 00:01:58.180
<v Speaker 1>When there's other words there, we might be really confused about where we can put it.

00:01:58.180 --> 00:02:04.259
<v Speaker 1>So we must think after the complete verb, the two form, or before the changed verb.

00:02:03.860 --> 00:02:09.539
<v Speaker 1>So if you say el lo terminado, you've actually got it after a changed verb.

00:02:09.539 --> 00:02:10.660
<v Speaker 1>You've got it after e.

00:02:10.739 --> 00:02:15.220
<v Speaker 1>So this is a very rare situation in Spanish where we have two changed verbs together

00:02:16.659 --> 00:02:20.019
<v Speaker 1>We see usually after change verb we get a complete verb.

00:02:20.019 --> 00:02:21.780
<v Speaker 1>Quiero terminar.

00:02:21.780 --> 00:02:23.459
<v Speaker 1>I want to finish.

00:02:23.459 --> 00:02:25.379
<v Speaker 1>Puedo terminar.

00:02:25.379 --> 00:02:27.459
<v Speaker 1>I can to finish.

00:02:28.200 --> 00:02:29.959
<v Speaker 1>Debo terminar.

00:02:29.959 --> 00:02:33.079
<v Speaker 1>I must, I owe, to finish.

00:02:33.079 --> 00:02:35.000
<v Speaker 1>So here we have to change verbs together.

00:02:35.079 --> 00:02:36.599
<v Speaker 1>E terminado.

00:02:36.599 --> 00:02:37.799
<v Speaker 1>Weird situation.

00:02:37.799 --> 00:02:40.439
<v Speaker 1>Which means there's only one place it can go.

00:02:40.240 --> 00:02:41.680
<v Speaker 2>Before the E.

00:02:41.680 --> 00:02:42.160
<v Speaker 1>Yes.

00:02:42.160 --> 00:02:43.840
<v Speaker 2>It's lo e terminado.

00:02:43.840 --> 00:02:44.160
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:02:44.160 --> 00:02:45.600
<v Speaker 1>Lo è terminado.

00:02:45.600 --> 00:02:47.040
<v Speaker 1>And I finished them

00:02:48.640 --> 00:02:50.320
<v Speaker 2>Los he terminado.

00:02:50.320 --> 00:02:52.240
<v Speaker 1>Los he terminado.

00:02:52.240 --> 00:02:57.440
<v Speaker 1>So with R verbs, we take off the R and we put Ado.

00:02:57.120 --> 00:03:07.840
<v Speaker 1>With er-ir verbs, we take away the er or the ir and we put ido to get this form of the verb that we need after aber.

00:03:07.640 --> 00:03:09.799
<v Speaker 2>Whether it's a ni there's no edo.

00:03:09.799 --> 00:03:17.319
<v Speaker 1>No, like I said, there's only one difference between er and ir verbs in all of the Spanish language.

00:03:17.319 --> 00:03:22.360
<v Speaker 1>Only one occasion where they're doing things differently, and that was in the present for we.

00:03:22.420 --> 00:03:28.980
<v Speaker 1>So for example, we have vender, which means to sell, and how do you say we sell?

00:03:29.460 --> 00:03:30.580
<v Speaker 1>Ventemos.

00:03:30.580 --> 00:03:30.980
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:03:30.980 --> 00:03:35.140
<v Speaker 1>And we had venir to come, and how do you say we come

00:03:35.980 --> 00:03:36.940
<v Speaker 1>Venimos.

00:03:36.940 --> 00:03:37.740
<v Speaker 1>Venimos.

00:03:37.740 --> 00:03:40.300
<v Speaker 1>So we had emos and emos.

00:03:40.300 --> 00:03:45.180
<v Speaker 1>This is the only time in the whole Spanish language that these two verbs are doing something differently.

00:03:45.120 --> 00:03:48.640
<v Speaker 1>To get this form of the verb that we need after aber.

00:03:48.640 --> 00:03:50.000
<v Speaker 1>Everything goes to ido.

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:53.840
<v Speaker 1>So vender becomes vendido.

00:03:53.840 --> 00:03:54.560
<v Speaker 1>Vendido.

00:03:54.560 --> 00:03:56.080
<v Speaker 1>And venir becomes

00:03:57.060 --> 00:03:57.940
<v Speaker 2>Venido.

00:03:57.940 --> 00:03:58.580
<v Speaker 1>Venido.

00:03:58.580 --> 00:04:02.740
<v Speaker 1>Now we understand where is bienvenido from.

00:04:02.740 --> 00:04:04.020
<v Speaker 1>Welcome.

